\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Strong:
\series default
 The two people are very close to each other, often sharing much of their
 lives with each other and confiding in each other for comfort and support.
 This often applies to those such as typical married couples, very close
 friends, parents and their children, or family of choice.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Medium:
\series default
 The two people are on friendly terms with each other and come to know each
 other on deeper terms.
 This often applies to those such as good friends, confidants, siblings,
 or a typical dating couple.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Weak:
\series default
 The two people have met each other before, and interact on occasion but
 rarely in particular depth.
 This often applies to those such as coworkers, gaming partners, extended
 family, or a friend of a friend.
 Hostile or unfriendly relationships also fall under this category, though
 some kinds of ambiguous relationships (such as a passionate rivalry) can
 justify stronger Intimacy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Described:
\series default
 You have a basic idea of who the person is, but have not interacted directly
 in any significant manner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These bonds must be mutual and cannot be strained by formal contexts or
 ingenious premises.
